	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				  The first thing that I would do would be to put your 5 skill points in one hand slashing.  Some people might disagree with this, but I feel that it is necessary if you do not want to die early on.  My rule of thumb is not to put more than 5 skill points in anything that you can build up on your own.  It's also a good idea to put some points in minor skills just to get them started off.  I started out in Freeport, but the following strategy will pretty much apply at any city.  As far as the difficulty for enemies goes, it pretty much gets harder the farther away you get from your starting city.  For your first 4 levels, I would recommend that you stay directly outside of the city killing enemies that are either evenly matched to you, or that you have the upper hand on.  Make sure that you have &quot;lay hands&quot; in your hotkey section.  Also stay close to the guards at first if you have already used it.  <BR>
  At level 1, you want to kill and then rest after each fight.  Keep everything that is left by your slain enemies and sell them once you level.  <BR>
  At level 2, you can kill more enemies before resting.  It's going to take you a little longer to level, but you still want to kill the same enemies you fought at level 1.  This process can get rather drawn out, but the more you fight the better you get at your skills.  It will be enough incentive when you see your 1 hand slashing, offense, and defense skills increasing.  Go ahead and keep whatever your corpses leave behind and sell them when you run out of room.  Whenever you have the money, buy whatever cheap armor and better weapons that you can afford.<BR>
  At level 3 and 4, you are finally ready for some better enemies.  Now you are going to want to fight beatles and enemies that walk around on two feet.  Only keep the items that you find on more intelligent enemies because they are worth much more.  You usually get weapons, armor, and money from these enemies.  I still wouldn't recommend drifting too far away from the city until you are a level 5.<BR>
  For levels 5 through 9, you are going to have trouble finding enemies( at least at Freeport ) that are around your level.  I would recommend the Steamfont Mountains.  There is a plethora of enemies for you to fight in this area.  Also, when you travel long distances like these, it gives you the chance to build up on sense direction.  As you run or just sit in place to rest, keep tapping the sense direction button and watch it increase in skill.  By this time you should have a good collection of armor.  Stay around the entrance of Steamfont for safety because there are occasionally some really tough monsters hanging around.  The nice thing about this area is that it is close to Felwith and Kelethin so you can pick up a bow and some arrows and work on your archery skills.  There are also bucklers if you haven't already bought a shield.  <BR>
  I don't have much more to offer to you at this point, but I hope that this will help the new adventurer.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
